ENV Variables — How to Find Them
Method 1 — Search for os.Getenv in Code
This is the most reliable method. Every language has a way to read env vars:
bash# Search entire codebase at once
grep -r "os.Getenv" .          # Go
grep -r "process.env" .        # Node.js
grep -r "os.environ" .         # Python
grep -r "System.getenv" .      # Java
In your ShopVerse backend:
bashgrep -r "os.Getenv" ./backend
Output:
database.go: dbUser     := getEnv("DB_USER", "shopverse")
database.go: dbPassword := getEnv("DB_PASSWORD", "shopverse123")
database.go: dbHost     := getEnv("DB_HOST", "localhost")
database.go: dbPort     := getEnv("DB_PORT", "3306")
database.go: dbName     := getEnv("DB_NAME", "shopverse")
main.go:     port       := os.Getenv("PORT")
main.go:     frontendOrigin := os.Getenv("FRONTEND_ORIGIN")
Every env var your app needs is RIGHT THERE. All in one search.

Method 2 — Look at .env.example file
Good developers always leave an example env file:
bash# .env.example
PORT=8080
DB_HOST=localhost
DB_PORT=3306
DB_USER=shopverse
DB_PASSWORD=shopverse123
DB_NAME=shopverse
JWT_SECRET=your-secret-key
FRONTEND_ORIGIN=http://localhost:3000
This is literally a list of all env vars the app needs. Copy them straight into your Dockerfile or docker-compose.

