Now Apply to Your ShopVerse Dockerfile
Step 1 — grep for env vars
bashgrep -r "os.Getenv\|getEnv" ./backend
Step 2 — You find ALL of these
PORT            default: 8080
FRONTEND_ORIGIN default: http://localhost:3000
DB_USER         default: shopverse
DB_PASSWORD     default: shopverse123
DB_HOST         default: localhost
DB_PORT         default: 3306
DB_NAME         default: shopverse
Step 3 — Write your Dockerfile
dockerfileFROM golang:1.24-alpine AS builder
RUN apk add --no-cache git
WORKDIR /app
COPY go.mod go.sum ./
RUN go mod download
COPY . .
RUN CGO_ENABLED=0 GOOS=linux go build \
    -ldflags="-w -s" \
    -o shopverse-backend \
    ./cmd/main.go

FROM alpine:3.19
RUN apk add --no-cache ca-certificates tzdata
RUN adduser -D -s /bin/sh appuser
WORKDIR /app
COPY --from=builder /app/shopverse-backend .
USER appuser

# ── Port found from main.go ──────────────
EXPOSE 8080

# ── Env vars found from grep ─────────────
# Safe defaults only — secrets passed at runtime!
ENV PORT=8080
ENV FRONTEND_ORIGIN=http://localhost:3000
ENV DB_HOST=localhost
ENV DB_PORT=3306
ENV DB_NAME=shopverse

# DB_PASSWORD and JWT_SECRET → NOT hardcoded here!
# Pass them at runtime:
# docker run -e DB_PASSWORD=xxx -e JWT_SECRET=yyy

CMD ["./shopverse-backend"]

Important Rule — What to Hardcode vs What NOT to
SAFE to hardcode in Dockerfile     NOT safe — pass at runtime
──────────────────────────────     ──────────────────────────
PORT=8080                          DB_PASSWORD=xxx
DB_HOST=localhost                  JWT_SECRET=xxx
DB_PORT=3306                       API_KEY=xxx
DB_NAME=shopverse                  AWS_SECRET=xxx
FRONTEND_ORIGIN=http://...

These are non-sensitive defaults     These are secrets!
Anyone can see them anyway           docker inspect reveals them
                                     use K8s secrets or .env file

